##Should a new stimulus be launched after the outbreak?

I-CAIJING

CAIJING magazine official Wechat. "CAIJING" magazine, sponsored by the China Securities Market Research Center, was first published in 1998, adhering to the news concept of "independence, exclusiveness and originality" , and is known for authoritative, impartial and professional reporting, it is a must-read publication for policy-makers, researchers and managers in the field of politics and economics.

We need to learn from the lessons of the 4 trillion yuan stimulus plan in the aftermath of the 2008 global financial crisis and reflect on where China's economic stimulus plan and policy priorities should be and where there is much to be done in the aftermath of the epidemic, where to exercise restraint

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Image / visual China

By Adrian Cheng

At the beginning of the crisis, some economists have suggested that China launch a new round of economic stimulus to achieve the goal of maintaining stable employment growth. Remember that in 2008, there was an ongoing debate among economists about whether China should launch a $4 trillion stimulus package in response to the global financial crisis. Although some scholars support the introduction of 4 trillion economic stimulus plan, there are many economists explicitly opposed to the poison to quench thirst of economic stimulus plan.

Yet the debate over a post-epidemic stimulus package has seen almost one-sided support. Some scholars call the new stimulus plan "version 2.0 of the 4 trillion yuan plan" , while others call it "new infrastructure" to distinguish it from "old infrastructure" such as the traditional "iron infrastructure" . Some provinces and cities began to prepare, and even issued a large number of large-scale key project investment plans. There is a need for more discussion.

Face up to the effects and side effects of the 4 trillion stimulus of the year

The 4 trillion yuan stimulus package in 2008 partly damped the downward trend of economic growth at the time and helped China's economy recover quickly after the global financial crisis. But a brief review of the major economic policies enacted over the past decade will shed light on the side effects of that stimulus.

One is that China has for a long time launched supply-side structural reforms that focus on "cutting capacity, deleveraging and Zombie" . At the heart of this is the huge excess capacity created by the previous stimulus, and the huge debts incurred by some local governments and state owned enterprises in the stimulus and subsequent inertia. Government departments at all levels have even resorted to one-size-fits-all administrative measures to eliminate excess capacity in steel, coal and photovoltaic production. Some state-owned enterprises with serious overcapacity continue to maintain new overcapacity through merger and restructuring, and some private enterprises are dying in the administrative action of capacity reduction. Despite the efforts of governments at all levels to cut production capacity, recent inventories of products such as steel in China have set new records.

The other is to guard against systemic financial risks. This policy is partly a continuation of the deleveraging policy in supply-side structural reform. For a period of time, many enterprises of different sizes and different business scope have frequent thunderstorms, and the relevant regulatory agencies have to take over the individual enterprises that are involved in too wide scope. Of course, this has to do with the aggressive expansion policies adopted by some enterprises, the speed of expansion and the degree of diversification, but it also has something to do with the legacy of the stimulus and the idea of paying down old debt with new debt. In addition to the thunderstorm in some state-owned enterprises, some local government debts remain high, and a new debt repayment peak is approaching, becoming another focus of work to prevent systemic financial risks. Some local governments have more debt than the next few decades'static revenues combined. Faced with these state-owned enterprises and local government debts can not be repaid on time, resulting in huge bad debts, we have to emphasize the importance of preventing and resolving systemic financial risks.

The third is the reform of mixed ownership of state-owned enterprises. Starting in 2013, China's state-owned enterprises began a new round of reform characterized by a mixture of ownership. It is not hard to see that some of the state owned enterprises that have been reinventing themselves have been the beneficiaries of the stimulus packages launched in response to the global financial crisis since 2008. Under the stimulus of that round of investment, some state-owned enterprises blindly expanded their production capacity, so that they fell into the predicament of excess capacity, and had to export excess capacity through direct reduction of production capacity, or even international cooperation. Its direct economic consequence is the benefit of these enterprises drops, their mechanism system problem that is concealed temporarily in the process of rapid expansion is exposed. To this end, by promoting the reform of mixed ownership, on the one hand to share the risk of the newly introduced war investment, on the other hand, to promote the transformation of these state-owned enterprises operating mechanism and improve the efficiency of state-owned enterprises.

These three aspects have formed part of the main theme of China's economic policy over the past decade. A theme behind these policies has always been defusing the negative effects of the $4 trillion stimulus package.

Like any keynesian-led stimulus, China's $4 trillion plan to deal with the global financial crisis in 2008 was also "heartening" and causing many to "jump for Joy" . Some state-owned enterprises welcomed it because they were the direct beneficiaries of the stimulus package. Some state-owned enterprises grew up or even strengthened for a time under the stimulus package. Some private enterprises also welcomed it, investors in the capital markets also welcomed the investment stimulus plan as a sign of a new bull market, as did some government officials, because the new project approval has created new achievements and potential rent-seeking opportunities, many cadres have also fallen on it in the past decade.

It was in the hands of some state owned enterprises, private companies, capital markets and government officials that the $4 trillion stimulus package was rolled out in an unstoppable fashion, and the economists who called for it were welcomed.

However, some of the state-owned enterprises that became large or even strong in the stimulus program were later dragged down by overcapacity and Zombie enterprises, and had to be the targets of state-owned enterprise restructuring and assets reorganization; Some of the private enterprises that benefited from this phenomenon have to suffer from frequent thunderstorms due to excessive expansion and excessive debt. In 2008, the Shanghai Stock Exchange index stood at around 3,000 points, and more than a decade later, the Shanghai Stock Exchange index still stood at around 3,000 points In the course of that stimulus, some government officials who used their power to seek rents were jailed in the ensuing crackdown on corruption.

If a new, larger stimulus package is needed to deal with the new crown disease and the already sluggish economic growth, will we face far more severe side effects and sequelae in the next decade than we did then? Will China's economy fall into new "traps" that are harder to extricate itself from?

What policies are more needed to ensure stable employment growth?

Even if we have to look for possible stimulus policies to keep job growth steady, can we do it more by cutting taxes than by increasing spending, more by guiding private capital investment, relying on market forces to cultivate new growth momentum? The practice of China's economic reform over the past 40 years has proved time and again that only when small and medium-sized enterprises (smes) are flourishing and private enterprises are growing strong, can more social employment be accommodated and new "stabilizers" be created for sustainable economic growth.

Although some scholars have warned that the new economic stimulus plan will focus on "new infrastructure" investment, and many of the important infrastructure and industrial investment have strategic value, but if fiscal investment still dominates in the implementation process, with state-owned enterprises as the main force, and not relying on private capital, which has a clearer profit motive and can bear the consequences of poor decision-making, to identify potential investment projects that meet market needs, then it seems that new infrastructure investments, there is still a risk of falling into the same fate as the old infrastructure investment, which could lead to a new round of investment inefficiency and related overcapacity.

Even if we have to look for possible economic stimulus policies in order to maintain steady job growth, can we move toward a more determined and aggressive mix of competitive ownership around the state owned enterprises that are actively advancing? On the one hand, the mixed transformation of state-owned enterprises can provide a broader space and stage for the development of private capital by introducing the battle and investment of the private capital background. On the other hand, it can promote the transformation of the operating mechanism of state-owned enterprises through the participation of private capital in corporate governance, improve the efficiency of state-owned enterprises, so as to avoid the concentration of resources in some inefficient state-owned enterprises, which is a drag on the speed and quality of China's economic growth.

Even if we have to seek possible economic stimulus policies in order to ensure steady employment growth, can we encourage more private and foreign capital to enter by opening up some restricted entry sectors, lowering the entry threshold for relevant sectors, to improve the quality of development of related industries and the economy as a whole by introducing competition mechanism? For example, the vulnerability of the Public Health Defense System exposed by the new outbreak is related to the chronic underinvestment in public health on the one hand, and the insufficient participation in the health care industry by relying on market input on the other, in the medical industry too much rely on financial investment, resulting in the crowding out of public health investment, and ultimately lose. Next, can we encourage more private and foreign capital to enter the field of medical services, increase effective supply, improve the quality of medical services, lower service prices, and correspondingly increase the financial input of the United States Public Health Service, which belongs to public goods.

As the outbreak of the new crown disease was contained, some people began to think about how to strengthen the public health defense system. Similarly, we need to reflect on the lessons of the 4 trillion yuan stimulus plan after the global financial crisis in 2008, where China's economic stimulus plan and policy priorities should be and where there is much to be done in the aftermath of the epidemic, where to exercise restraint.

(the writer is professor of Finance, Renmin University of China, and Editor: He Gang)
